    overviewDetailed: "NID Bangalore is a compact, ~2-acre campus that is part of the seven-campus National Institute of Design network, and offers only postgraduate M.Des programmes (no B.Des) — making it a specialised, research- and industry-facing extension rather than a full undergraduate design school. Its location in Bengaluru is a deliberate positioning to connect design education directly with the city technology and product-design industry, particularly for Digital Game Design and Interaction Design.",
    coursesFeesDetailed: 'Programme: M.Des (Master of Design) — 2.5-year (2 years 6 months) full-time programme across 5 specialisations (Digital Game Design, Interaction Design, Information Design, Universal Design), each with roughly 19 seats; also offers a PhD in Design (full-time and part-time). M.Des total fee (2026-27): approximately INR 13.28 Lakh for Indian National students for the entire duration; first-year tuition specifically is cited around INR 5.25 Lakh. PhD fee (2026-27): approximately INR 2.29 Lakh for the entire 3-year duration. Fee structure differs by category: Indian Nationals, Rest-of-World students, and SAARC/African-countries/Cambodia/Laos/Myanmar students are charged differently. Fee components include tuition, hostel, mess and miscellaneous charges. Limited merit-based scholarships available; financially weak students may receive a full tuition-fee waiver from NID and the Government of India.',
    admissionDetailed: 'Eligibility (M.Des): A Bachelor degree from a recognised university/institute in any discipline, completed over a minimum of 3-4 years (or equivalent foreign degree). Step 1 — NID DAT Prelims: a written test assessing design aptitude, innovation and problem-solving ability, held at multiple centres across India. Step 2 — NID DAT Mains: shortlisted Prelims candidates undergo material-handling aptitude tests and discipline-specific evaluation. Step 3 — Studio Test: practical design assignments assessing hands-on skills. Step 4 — Personal Interview: assessing motivation and suitability for the chosen M.Des discipline. Application process: register on the official NID admissions portal, select the M.Des programme and up to two disciplines, upload documents, pay the non-refundable application fee, and submit. NID does not publish an official DAT cutoff; selection is a composite of DAT score, Studio Test and Interview performance.',
    placementsDetailed: 'NID Industry Interface and Placement (IIP) unit runs placements centrally across all NID campuses — recruiters can hire NID Bangalore talent through a unified national process rather than a campus-specific one. 2024 placement drive: highest salary package of INR 30 LPA recorded. Average alumni package is cited around INR 8-10 LPA across sources. The IIP Cell coordinates biannual placement drives, portfolio reviews, mock interviews, professional-development workshops, grooming sessions and industry-exposure events. NID Bangalore placement strength is described as strong (80-95% range in some estimates) given its niche specialisation in digital, interaction and game design — fields with high demand from Bengaluru tech industry. The institute also facilitates internships and graduation-project placements as an additional route into full-time offers.',
    campusDetailed: 'Compact ~2-acre, non-residential campus in Yeshwanthpur, Bengaluru — students typically arrange private PG/hostel accommodation nearby rather than residing on-campus. Fully air-conditioned classrooms and labs, including a dedicated Universal Design Lab for innovation using modern design technology. Active industry-research partnerships, including the Digital Hampi Lab (digital reconstruction of Hampi monuments) and e-Kalpa Lab (digital learning environment for design), reflecting NID applied-research orientation. Ragging-free campus with on-appointment student counselling support, a guest-room facility for visiting parents, and on-campus medical facilities. Strong faculty expertise specifically in digital, interaction, universal and game design.',
    cutoffDetailed: "NID does not publish an official numeric DAT cutoff for Bangalore M.Des programmes; selection is determined by a weighted combination of DAT Prelims, DAT Mains, Studio Test and Interview scores. A previously reported DAT cutoff for a comparable NID cycle was approximately 89.47%, though this varies year to year and by specialisation. Selection is highly competitive given the limited intake (~19 seats per specialisation), making NID Bangalore M.Des among the more selective postgraduate design admissions nationally. Merit lists and seat allotment are communicated during a counselling phase, where candidates must bring original documents and photocopies to confirm their seat.",
